  "prompt": "Is there anything bigger than the universe?",
  "response": "This is a fascinating question that touches on the limits of our current scientific understanding. According to our current cosmological models:\n\n1. Observable Universe: This is the part of the universe we can see, limited by the speed of light and the age of the universe.\n\n2. Entire Universe: Cosmologists aren't certain whether the universe is finite or infinite. Some theories suggest:\n- The universe might be infinite in size\n- There could be multiple universes (multiverse theory)\n- Our universe might be part of a larger structure we don't yet comprehend\n\n3. Theoretical Possibilities:\n- Some quantum theories propose parallel universes\n- String theory suggests additional dimensions beyond our perception\n- Speculative models like \"bubble universes\" exist\n\n4. Scientific Limitations:\n- We can only observe and measure what our current technology allows\n- Many cosmological ideas remain theoretical\n- Our understanding is continually evolving\n\nWhile we can't definitively say something is \"bigger\" than the universe, scientific research continues to explore these profound questions about cosmic scale and structure.\n\nThe honest scientific answer is: We don't know for certain, but we're actively researching and developing new theories to understand the nature of our cosmos.",
